<methodology slug="difficult-conversations">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>comms</group>
    <domain>communicator</domain>
    <summary>Crucial Conversations framework structures high-stakes conversations through seven sequential skills including safety, story separation, and structured dialogue using STATE and DESC techniques.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>difficult-conversations</tag>
      <tag>crucial-conversations</tag>
      <tag>state-desc</tag>
      <tag>communication</tag>
      <tag>high-stakes</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Difficult Conversations</title>
    <summary>The Crucial Conversations framework structures high-stakes conversations (high stakes + differing opinions + strong emotions) through seven sequential skills: Start with Heart → Learn to Look → Make it Safe → Master My Stories → STATE My Path → Explore Others' Paths → Move to Action. The DESC script (Describe + Express + Specify + Consequences) is a shorter format for written boundary-setting. Both require separation of observable facts from interpretations before any message is drafted.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Avoiding difficult conversations causes festering resentment, repeated problems, damaged trust, and eventual explosion. The most common failure modes are: waiting too long (address within 3-5 days), using email or text instead of face-to-face, bringing up the past instead of the current issue, and failing to end with a specific WHO/WHAT/WHEN commitment. A well-prepared script reduces anxiety and prevents the conversation from derailing into defensive arguments.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Preparing a script for a performance issue conversation separating observable facts from interpretations</item>
        <item>Drafting a DESC-structured written message to set a boundary (e.g., after-hours messaging, scope creep)</item>
        <item>Converting a reactive emotional draft into a STATE-structured, fact-based opening</item>
        <item>Running through the preparation checklist before a high-stakes conversation (saying no to a boss, peer conflict, systemic problem)</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Active crisis conversations requiring real-time de-escalation — agents cannot adapt to live emotional cues</item>
        <item>HR formal disciplinary processes where documented language must follow legal requirements</item>
        <item>Conversations involving significant power asymmetry where organizational political context is required</item>
        <item>Anonymous feedback or 360-review contexts where protecting identity is the goal</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Skill 1: Start with Heart">
      <rule>
        <statement>Before starting a crucial conversation, answer four questions: What do I want for me? For them? For the relationship? For the organization? Behave as if you truly want all four outcomes simultaneously.</statement>
        <rationale>Hidden agendas (wanting to win, wanting to punish) produce scripts that are technically correct but destroy safety. The other person detects misalignment between words and intent.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Reject the "Fool's Choice" framing — "Either I speak up and damage the relationship, OR I stay silent and the problem continues." Both honesty and respect are achievable simultaneously.</statement>
        <rationale>The Fool's Choice is a cognitive distortion that prevents creative solutions. Accepting it makes avoidance feel justified.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Skill 2: Learn to Look — Safety Signals">
      <rule>
        <statement>Watch for silence signals (masking with sarcasm, avoiding the topic, withdrawing) and violence signals (controlling the conversation, labeling, personal attacks). When either appears, pause content and restore safety before continuing.</statement>
        <rationale>Safety violations are the most reliable predictor of a conversation going off the rails. Content cannot land when the other person is in fight-or-flight mode.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Silence: sarcasm, changing subject, one-word answers, shutting down</item>
        <item>Violence: cutting off, overstating, labeling ("you're being defensive"), personal criticism</item>
        <item>Physical: arms crossed, looking away, raised voice, tears, flushed face</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Skill 3: Make it Safe">
      <rule>
        <statement>Restore safety with Mutual Purpose (show you care about their goals), Mutual Respect (show you value them), Contrasting (clarify what you are NOT saying), or Apology (when genuinely appropriate).</statement>
        <rationale>Safety is not the absence of disagreement — it is the belief that you can express yourself without being attacked or dismissed. Restoring it requires explicit action, not just tonal adjustment.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Mutual Purpose: "I want to find a solution that works for both of us."</item>
        <item>Contrasting: "I'm not saying you're incompetent. I am saying this specific approach has caused problems."</item>
        <item>Apology: "I'm sorry I didn't raise this sooner. That wasn't fair to you."</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Skill 4: Master My Stories">
      <rule>
        <statement>Separate the observable fact, the story you told about it, and the feeling that story produced. Challenge victim stories ("They don't respect me") by reframing as ownership stories ("I haven't clearly communicated my needs").</statement>
        <rationale>Stories drive feelings, and feelings drive actions. Changing the story changes the emotional state and opens different behavioral options.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Fact, story, feeling separation">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[FACT: "You submitted the report on Thursday."
STORY: "You don't care about deadlines." (interpretation — not fact)
FEELING: "I'm frustrated."

Reframe: "You may have had constraints I don't know about." (ownership story)
New feeling: "I'm curious about what happened."]]></code>
      </example>
      <list>
        <item>Victim story: "They don't respect me" → Ownership: "I haven't clearly communicated my needs"</item>
        <item>Victim story: "They're incompetent" → Ownership: "They might have constraints I don't know"</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Skill 5: STATE My Path">
      <rule>
        <statement>Open with observable facts (not interpretations), share your tentative story, then immediately invite the other person's perspective. The opening must be deliverable in under 60 seconds — 3-5 sentences maximum.</statement>
        <rationale>Openings longer than 60 seconds read as monologues. "Talk tentatively" ("I might be missing something") is not weakness — it is the signal that invites the other party to contribute.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="STATE opening structure">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[S: "The last three milestones were delivered 2-3 days late." (Share facts — observable)
T: "I'm starting to worry about whether we'll hit the launch date." (Tell story — tentative)
A: "Can you help me understand what's happening?" (Ask for their path)
T: "I might be missing context." (Talk tentatively)
E: "I'm open to hearing I'm wrong about this." (Encourage testing)]]></code>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Ending the STATE opening with a rhetorical question ("You see that this is a problem, right?") instead of a genuine inquiry.</description>
        <reason>Rhetorical questions destroy the safety that the rest of STATE was building. The other person reads them as a trap.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Skill 6: AMPP — Exploring Others' Paths">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use AMPP to understand the other person's perspective: Ask (open questions), Mirror (reflect emotions back), Paraphrase (restate content), Prime (guess their feeling if they seem stuck).</statement>
        <rationale>AMPP prevents the common failure of preparing your rebuttal while the other person is still speaking. Genuine listening requires structured attention.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Ask: "What's your view?" — open the door</item>
        <item>Mirror: "You seem frustrated about this." — reflect what you observe</item>
        <item>Paraphrase: "So you're saying the timeline was unrealistic from the start?" — confirm</item>
        <item>Prime: "Are you worried about how this will affect your team's workload?" — guess if stuck</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="DESC — Written Boundary-Setting">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use DESC for written communication (Slack, email) when a live conversation is not possible or to follow up after one. Never read DESC aloud in a meeting as a script.</statement>
        <rationale>DESC is calibrated for written async delivery. Read aloud, it sounds prepared and clinical — destroying the rapport required for a live difficult conversation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="DESC script for boundary-setting">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[D (Describe): "When I receive Slack messages at 10pm expecting an immediate response..."
E (Express): "I feel stressed and unable to disconnect from work..."
S (Specify): "I would like us to agree that non-urgent messages can wait until morning..."
C (Consequences): "This would help me be more focused during work hours.
If it continues, I'll need to turn off notifications entirely."]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Skill 7: WWWF — Move to Action">
      <rule>
        <statement>End every difficult conversation with WHO does WHAT by WHEN and a scheduled follow-up date. Vague commitment ("we'll do better") is not an agreement.</statement>
        <rationale>Without specific accountability, both parties leave with different interpretations of what was agreed. Follow-up date closes the loop and signals the issue is being tracked.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Agent Usage and Limitations">
      <p>An agent assists difficult conversations in two phases: preparation and drafting. In the preparation phase, the agent receives the raw situation and runs through the Crucial Conversations preparation checklist, prompting the human to supply: what they want for each party, the factual observations (not stories), their contribution to the problem, and the other party's likely perspective. In the drafting phase, the agent generates a STATE-structured opening script and a DESC-structured message if a written boundary is appropriate. The agent should produce a draft, then perform a self-check: does every statement use observable facts? Is the request specific? Is there a genuine question inviting the other party's perspective?</p>
      <p>Limitations: The Crucial Conversations framework requires the human to genuinely "Start with Heart" (know what they want) before the script is useful; a well-drafted script with a hidden agenda will fail in the conversation. Agents can structure the STATE sequence correctly but cannot verify that the "facts" provided are truly factual and not the human's interpretations — human must do this pre-verification step. Tone in text-based drafts reads differently than the same words spoken; agent-produced scripts may sound more aggressive or more passive than intended in live delivery. WWWF commitment templates require follow-up scheduling that agents cannot initiate autonomously.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Separate facts from stories before writing anything — list raw observations (timestamps, measurable behaviors) and explicitly mark any interpretation as a "story to be tested"</item>
        <item>The STATE script must end with a genuine question, not a rhetorical one; "I'm open to hearing I've got this wrong" must be sincere or it breaks safety immediately</item>
        <item>DESC scripts are for written communication only (Slack, email) when a live conversation is not possible — they are not scripts to read aloud in a meeting</item>
        <item>Address issues early (3-5 day window from the event); agents drafted a week after the fact tend to produce scripts that reference stale context the other party has moved on from</item>
        <item>Prepare the fallback scenario (what you will do if the conversation goes poorly) before the conversation; agents can generate this as a separate section in the prep document</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
      <note>Agents may produce STATE scripts that are technically correct but too long for an opening — the opening should be deliverable in under 60 seconds; instruct the agent to keep the initial script to 3-5 sentences.</note>
      <note>"Masking" safety violations (sarcasm, sugarcoating) are hard for agents to detect in human-provided drafts; human must self-assess the tone before input reaches the agent.</note>
      <note>Human checkpoint required before using any agent-drafted script in a real conversation — verify every factual claim and that the tone matches the actual relationship.</note>
      <note>Agents asked to prepare a "saying no to boss" script may produce overly deferential language that undermines the message; specify the desired assertiveness level explicitly.</note>
      <note>AMPP questions generated by agents for live conversations must be memorized and paraphrased, not read from a list; reading questions in a difficult conversation destroys rapport.</note>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/preparation-checklist.md" purpose="Pre-conversation checklist: goals, facts, contribution, their perspective, safety risks"/>
      <template path="templates/wwwf-tracker.md" purpose="Post-conversation commitment tracker (Who/What/When/Follow-up)"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-state-script.txt" purpose="Prompt for generating a STATE-structured opening script"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-desc-script.txt" purpose="Prompt for writing a DESC boundary-setting message"/>
    </templates>
